Introduction Oftentimes, your program will need to allocate memory on the heap. Unlike the stack where deallocations occur upon scope exiting, something needs to explicitly free memory from the heap.
In some languages like $	exttt{C}$, it is the programmer&rsquo;s responsibility to call $	exttt{free}$ when it is no longer needed. Manual memory leak debugging and tests were required (i.e. valgrind).
A lot of higher-level programming languages have a &ldquo;garbage collector&rdquo; (gc). Aptly named, they execute independently of the main program and free memory that is no longer being used (garbage).
Techniques Garbage collection is a difficult task. There is a juggling tradeoff between the completeness of the gc (what leaks can we allow) versus the resource complexity of the gc (time, space, processing).
Reference Counting For every allocated piece of memory, store a referencing counter representing the number of pointers that point to it. If it ever reaches $0$, free the memory chunk.
Algorithm $$  egin{align*} &amp;	exttt{on new $M$:}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad $M$.ref\_count = 1}
ewline &amp;
ewline &amp;	exttt{on $x$ = $M$:}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad $M$.ref\_count++}
ewline &amp;
ewline &amp;	exttt{on ($x$ = $M$) out of scope:}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad $M$.ref\_count--}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad if $M$.ref\_count = 0}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad \qquad free($M$)}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad \qquad recurse out-of-scope check on $M$ fields} \end{align*} $$
Pros Very simple to implement No background thread running in background (all operations are triggered) Cons Word overhead for storing $	exttt{ref\_count}$ per allocated memory block Chain overhead when freeing a linked data structure A B C D E F Imagine $	exttt{A}$ is freed. Then, $	exttt{B}$ is freed. Then, $	exttt{C}$ is freed. And so on. So there is a potential high overhead when freeing linked data structures (program pause).
Cycles leak memory A D B C These nodes point to each other. So, their $	exttt{ref\_count}$ will never be $0$ even if nothing else in the program points to them (should be garbage).
Python uses reference counting for its gc. Watch it leak by making a large number of cycle structures.
Mark Sweep For every allocated block of memory, store a mark bit (initialized to $0$). Every now and then, mark all memory that have pointers to them within the current program scope. Free all allocated memory that has not been marked (cannot be accessed $\implies$ garbage). Unmark all marks.
Algorithm $$  egin{align*} &amp;	exttt{let markRecurse(ptr $p$):}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad if $p$ is marked then return}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad mark $p$}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad for all pointers $f$ that are fields of $p$:}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad \qquad markRecurse($f$)}
ewline &amp;
ewline &amp;	exttt{on gc trigger:}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad pause program}
ewline &amp;
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad // mark phase}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad for all pointers $p$ in scope:}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad \qquad markRecurse($p$)}
ewline &amp;
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad // sweep phase}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad for all allocated memory blocks $b$:}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad \qquad if $b$ is marked then free($b$)}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad \qquad unmark $b$}
ewline &amp;
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad resume program} \end{align*} $$
The gc trigger is heuristical. It could be based on time intervals, memory utilization, processor utilization, etc.
Pros The gc will collect all garbage Cons Long pauses when gc is running Copy Collection Divide the heap into two equal sections: from and to. For every allocated block of memory, store a &ldquo;forwarding address&rdquo; (initialized to $0$). All newly allocated blocks are placed in the from space. Once full, the gc is triggered. It moves all non-garbage blocks to the to space and frees the from space. Then, it swaps the from and to space labels.
Algorithm $$  egin{align*} &amp;	exttt{let copyRecurse(ptr $p$):}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad if $p$ has no forwarding address:}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad \qquad let $m$ = next available block in $to$ space}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad \qquad copy non-ptr fields of $p$ into $m$}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad \qquad $p$ forwarding address = $m$ (in $from$ space)}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad \qquad for all ptr fields $f$ of $p$:}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad \qquad \qquad $f$ forwarding address = copyRecurse($f$)}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad return $p$ forwarding address}
ewline &amp;
ewline &amp;	exttt{on gc trigger:}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad pause program}
ewline &amp;
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad for all pointers $p$ in scope:}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad \qquad copyRecurse($p$)}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad free($from$ space)}
ewline &amp;
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad swap $to$ and $from$ labels}
ewline &amp;
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad resume program} \end{align*} $$
The &ldquo;forwarding address&rdquo; is for the gc to move cyclical data structures to the to space.
Without it, recursing on pointers to blocks already in the to space will move the same block again (essentially duplicating it infinitely in the to space).
f f r r o o m A B m A B t t o o A B f f r r o o m A B m A B t t o A o A B A Example f f r r o o m A B m t t o o A B f t r o o m B t f o A r A B o m Pros The gc will collect all garbage Efficient memory utilization (all allocations are contiguous: no fragmentation) Only $1$ iteration (as opposed to $2$ from mark/sweep) Cons Long pauses when gc is running Only half of the heap can be operated on at a time Lifetime Optimization A general analysis of programs yields the following result.
Allocated memory blocks that live past a certain point tend to live a really long time Other blocks tend to be short lived This sort of makes sense. These long lasting blocks are likely to be data structures that persist throughout the program. On the other hand, short lived blocks might be temporaries that we only need for a scope (i.e. within function).
An optimization to employ is generational collection. The heap is divided into two sections: nursery and tenured.
n u [ r n s e e w r ] y t e [ n o u l r d e ] d All newly allocated blocks are placed in the nursery. When a nursery gc triggers and cleans up the trash, all blocks that were not cleaned up are &ldquo;promoted&rdquo; to live in the tenured space. There is also a tenured gc, but that executes less frequently than the nursery gc (since those blocks are less likely to be garbage). Observe that after a nursery gc execution, the entire nursery is freed. Much like in copy collection, we can just reclaim the entire space at once rather than for each individual block.
Type Unsafe Problem Lots of higher-level programming languages have type systems that keep code &ldquo;safe&rdquo;. In a lower-level language like $	exttt{C/C++}$, anything goes. Specifically, any piece of data could be casted to a pointer.
For instance, $	exttt{int x = 5}$ could technically also be a pointer to the memory address $	exttt{0x5}$.
An approach is to employ conservative collection. Any data in scope is conservatively considered to be a pointer. If there exists allocated memory at the address specified by that data, then consider it &ldquo;not garbage&rdquo; (don&rsquo;t free it).
If we had $	exttt{int x = 5}$ and there was $	exttt{Object obj}$ allocated at address $	exttt{0x4}$ with size $	exttt{0x8}$, then consider $	exttt{obj}$ to be in use.
The reason being is that we could technically use $	exttt{x}$ to access $	exttt{obj}$, so we can&rsquo;t deem $	exttt{obj}$ as garbage yet.
It&rsquo;s a conservative approach because the gc might falsely mark a piece of memory as still in use, thus leaking it.

Introduction As implied by the name, phantom types are defined by type parameters that are not actually used in implementation. Instead, they are used by the type system to restrict operations on that type. We can use them to improve program correctness (by the type checker).
Examples Units Suppose we want to have a type for measurement units.
Definition $$  egin{align*} &amp;	exttt{module Unit : sig}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad type &lsquo;a t}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad val of\_float : float -&gt; &lsquo;a t}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad val (+.) : &lsquo;a t -&gt; &lsquo;a t -&gt; &lsquo;a t}
ewline &amp;	exttt{end = struct}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad type &lsquo;a t = float}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad let of\_float x = x}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad let (+.) = (+.)}
ewline &amp;	exttt{end} \end{align*} $$
The module syntax is for defining stuff (in this case types and functions) in a context. So you would have to call $	exttt{of\_float}$ with $	exttt{Unit.of\_float}$.
$	exttt{sig}$ represents the module signature and $	exttt{struct}$ represents its actual definition (you can have multiple $	exttt{struct}$ definitions for a single $	exttt{sig}$).
$	exttt{(+.)}$ is just an infix operator for float addition. Here, we define it for operations involving two values of type $	exttt{Unit}$.
Notice how $	exttt{&lsquo;a}$ is never actually used: its underlying type is just a $	exttt{float}$. However, notice that $	exttt{(+.)}$ has type $	exttt{&lsquo;a t -&gt; &lsquo;a t -&gt; &lsquo;a t}$. This means that the two parameters we pass into $	exttt{(+.)}$ better have the same $	exttt{&lsquo;a}$ type parameter. Similarly, it will return a value with that same $	exttt{&lsquo;a}$.
Use $$  egin{align*} &amp;	exttt{type meters}
ewline &amp;	exttt{type lbs}
ewline &amp;
ewline &amp;	exttt{open Unit}
ewline &amp;	exttt{let m1 : meters t = of\_float 2.}
ewline &amp;	exttt{let m2 : meters t = of\_float 4.}
ewline &amp;	exttt{let p1 : lbs t = of\_float 3.}
ewline &amp;	exttt{let p2 : lbs t = of\_float 5.}
ewline &amp;	exttt{let total\_m = m1 +. m2}
ewline &amp;	exttt{let total\_p = p1 +. p2} \end{align*} $$
$	exttt{open Unit}$ just allows us to access $	exttt{Unit}$ things without prepending them.
Notice how $	exttt{meter}$ and $	exttt{lbs}$ are never actually used outside of declaring types. This is how we can enforce that $	exttt{(+.)}$ operations can never be used on different units.
If you try to add units with different $	exttt{&lsquo;a}$ parameter types, your program will fail to type check.
$$\cancel{	exttt{total\_m (+.) total\_p}}$$
Also, if you try to instantiate a variable with a phantom type without the explicit $	exttt{&lsquo;a}$, your program will also fail to type check.
$$\cancel{	exttt{let x = of\_float 6.}}$$
Access Control This example was inspired by a Ron Minsky post.
Suppose we want to have a type for reference cells that have access control permissions (read and read/write).
Reference cells allow for mutable values by storing them as addresses containing the data.
$	exttt{let x = ref 10}$ creates a reference cell $	exttt{x}$ storing the value $	exttt{10}$. $	exttt{x := 4}$ sets the value in $	exttt{x}$ to $	exttt{4}$. $	exttt{let v = !x}$ extracts the value in $	exttt{x}$ (so $	exttt{v = 4}$). Definition $$  egin{align*} &amp;	exttt{type read}
ewline &amp;	exttt{type write}
ewline &amp;
ewline &amp;	exttt{module Ref : sig}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad type (&lsquo;a, &lsquo;b) t}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad create : &lsquo;b -&gt; (write, &lsquo;b) t}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad set : (write, &lsquo;b) t -&gt; &lsquo;b -&gt; unit}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad get : (&lsquo;a, &lsquo;b) t -&gt; &lsquo;b}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad readonly : (&lsquo;a, &lsquo;b) t -&gt; (read, &lsquo;b) t}
ewline &amp;	exttt{end = struct}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad type (&lsquo;a, &lsquo;b) t = &lsquo;b ref}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad create x = ref x}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad set t x = t := x}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad get x = !x}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad readonly x = x}
ewline &amp;	exttt{end} \end{align*} $$
$	exttt{&lsquo;a}$ is discarded in the definition of $	exttt{Ref}$ (what makes it a phantom type). $	exttt{&lsquo;b}$ just makes it polymorphic.
Polymorphic just means that the underlying type of the data within the cell can be anything. In the use example below, we will use $	exttt{&lsquo;b = int}$.
As shown, $	exttt{Ref}$ has $	exttt{&lsquo;a = write}$ access upon creation, and you can only call $	exttt{set}$ on a $	exttt{Ref}$ which has $	exttt{&lsquo;a = write}$. Additionally, you can cast any $	exttt{Ref}$ to have $	exttt{&lsquo;a = read}$ using $	exttt{readonly}$ without actually changing any of its underlying data (just its $	exttt{&lsquo;a}$ parameter type).
Use $$  egin{align*} &amp;	exttt{open Ref}
ewline &amp;	exttt{let write\_ref = create 10}
ewline &amp;	exttt{let read\_ref = readonly write\_ref}
ewline &amp;	exttt{let value1 = get write\_ref}
ewline &amp;	exttt{let () = set write\_ref 4}
ewline &amp;	exttt{let value2 = get read\_ref} \end{align*} $$
If you try to call $	exttt{set}$ on a $	exttt{Ref}$ with $	exttt{&lsquo;a = readonly}$, your program will fail to type check.
$$\cancel{	exttt{set read\_ref 4}}$$

Definition Monads are structures that wrap values. They are useful for creating computation pipelines that abstract away control flow and side effects.
Return and Bind A monad of type $	exttt{&lsquo;a t}$ has the following functions.
$$  egin{align*} &amp;	exttt{return: &lsquo;a -&gt; &lsquo;a t}
ewline &amp;	exttt{bind: &lsquo;a t -&gt; (&lsquo;a -&gt; &lsquo;b t) -&gt; &lsquo;b t} \end{align*} $$
Monads are parametric types. $	exttt{t}$ represents the monad itself and $	exttt{&lsquo;a}$ is the type parameter.
For example, $	exttt{Option}$ is a monad. The value it wraps has the parameter type $	exttt{&lsquo;a}$. So, you could have types like $	exttt{int Option}$ or $	exttt{string Option}$.
$	exttt{&lsquo;b}$ is another parameter. Bind takes a function that essentially &ldquo;maps&rdquo; the current monad type parameter $	exttt{&lsquo;a}$ to another monad of type $	exttt{&lsquo;b}$.
It helps to follow the types. $	exttt{return}$ constructs the monad from a value. $	exttt{bind}$ transforms the value within the monad (computation pipeline).
Map The definition for the monadic function $	exttt{map}$ follows from the functions above.
$$  egin{align*} &amp;	exttt{map: &lsquo;a t -&gt; (&lsquo;a -&gt; &lsquo;b) -&gt; &lsquo;b t}
ewline &amp;
ewline &amp;	exttt{let map t f =}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad let g a = return (f a) in}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad bind t g} \end{align*} $$
$	exttt{map}$ is the same as $	exttt{bind}$ except the function ($	exttt{f}$) returns a raw $	exttt{&lsquo;b}$ rather than a $	exttt{&lsquo;b t}$.
Here, we construct the $	exttt{g}$ necessary for $	exttt{bind}$ by just applying $	exttt{return}$ to the result of $	exttt{f}$.
OCaml ppx_let The ppx_let library for OCaml provides an elegant way to code with monads.
Although The ppx_let library introduces various monadic syntax (i.e. monadic pattern matching), we will only display monadic let bindings.
They work similarly to these monadic let bindings (see documentation).
$$  egin{align*} &amp;	exttt{let\%bind a = a\_monad in (* a : &lsquo;a; a\_monad : &lsquo;a t *)}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad &hellip;}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad b\_monad (* b\_monad : &lsquo;b t *)} \end{align*} $$
$	exttt{(* &hellip; *)}$ are comments.
With this syntactic sugar, we define the function parameter in (call it $	exttt{f}$ with type $	exttt{&lsquo;a -&gt; &lsquo;b t}$) in the body of the $	exttt{let\%bind}$, where $	exttt{a}$ is the parameter to $	exttt{f}$.
$$  egin{align*} &amp;	exttt{let\%map a = a\_monad in (* a : &lsquo;a; a\_monad : &lsquo;a t *)}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad &hellip;}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad b (* b : &lsquo;b *)} \end{align*} $$
$	exttt{let\%map}$ does basically the same thing except the return type of its body is just a $	exttt{&lsquo;b}$ (as is in $	exttt{f}$ with type $	exttt{&lsquo;a -&gt; &lsquo;b}$).
These might be easier to grasp with the examples below.
Important to note that the type of the entire $	exttt{let\%bind}$ and $	exttt{let\%map}$ expressions are $	exttt{&lsquo;b t}$, consistent with the return types of $	exttt{bind}$ and $	exttt{map}$.
Typically, to chain monadic operations we will end with a single $	exttt{let\%map}$. All previous bindings will be $	exttt{let\%bind}$.
$$  egin{align*} &amp;	exttt{let\%bind a = a\_monad in}
ewline &amp;	exttt{let\%bind b = b\_monad in}
ewline &amp;	exttt{let\%bind c = c\_monad in}
ewline &amp;	exttt{let\%map d = d\_monad in}
ewline &amp;	exttt{(a, b, c, d)} \end{align*} $$
Why is this the case?
$	exttt{let\%bind}$ expects its function parameter to return a monad, which both $	exttt{let\%bind}$ and $	exttt{let\%map}$ do. This is why all except the last level must be $	exttt{let\%bind}$. It is natural to perform computations without monads. Since this usually occurs after &ldquo;unwrapping&rdquo; all the monads, the last level is usually a $	exttt{let\%map}$. Note that if the last level were a $	exttt{let\%bind}$, we would have to return a monad.
$$  egin{align*} &amp;	exttt{let\%bind a = a\_monad in}
ewline &amp;	exttt{let\%bind b = b\_monad in}
ewline &amp;	exttt{let\%bind c = c\_monad in}
ewline &amp;	exttt{let\%bind d = d\_monad in}
ewline &amp;	exttt{return (a, b, c, d)} \end{align*} $$
Examples Option Definition Options give optionality to the existence of an underlying value.
$$  egin{align*} &amp;	exttt{type &lsquo;a Option =}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\quad | None}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\quad | Some of &lsquo;a}
ewline &amp;
ewline &amp;	exttt{let return a = Some a }
ewline &amp;	exttt{let bind a\_opt f =}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad match a\_opt with}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad \qquad None -&gt; None}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad \quad | Some a -&gt; f a} \end{align*} $$
Use Suppose we want to implement the $	exttt{option\_plus}$ function which operates on two parameters of type $	exttt{int Option}$.
$$  egin{align*} &amp;	exttt{let option\_plus (a\_opt : int Option) (b\_opt : int Option) : int Option =}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad let\%bind a = a\_opt in}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad let\%map b = b\_opt in}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad a + b} \end{align*} $$
This is much more elegant than &ldquo;if-statement spamming&rdquo; (or in OCaml, &ldquo;pattern match spamming&rdquo;).
$$  egin{align*} &amp;	exttt{let option\_plus (a\_opt : int Option) (b\_opt : int Option) : int Option =}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad match a\_opt with}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad \qquad None -&gt; None}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad \quad | Some a -&gt;}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad \qquad (match b\_opt with}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad \qquad \qquad None -&gt; None}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad \quad \qquad | Some b -&gt; a + b)} \end{align*} $$
Result Definition Results allow values to have a fail condition. They are like options except we can tag the $	exttt{None}$ case with information (i.e. error information).
$$  egin{align*} &amp;	exttt{type (&lsquo;a, &lsquo;b) Result =}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\quad | Ok of &lsquo;a}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\quad | Error of &lsquo;b}
ewline &amp;
ewline &amp;	exttt{let return a = Ok a }
ewline &amp;	exttt{let bind a\_res f =}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad match a\_res with}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad \qquad Ok a -&gt; f a}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad \quad | Error \_ as err -&gt; err} \end{align*} $$
The $	exttt{Error \_ as err -&gt; err}$ just assigns the entire result into $	exttt{err}$. Alternatively, we could have written $	exttt{Error e -&gt; Error e}$.
Use Suppose we have a function $	exttt{input: unit -&gt; string}$ which reads from $	exttt{stdin}$.
The $	exttt{unit}$ type has only one possible value: $	exttt{()}$. It is useful for when we want a function that requires zero arguments.
Suppose we have a function which attempts to convert a $	exttt{string}$ to an $	exttt{int}$ and stores the error as a $	exttt{string}$.
$$	exttt{atoi: string -&gt; (int, string) Result}$$
Now, let&rsquo;s write a function to add two user inputs.
$$  egin{align*} &amp;	exttt{let add\_user\_inputs (() : unit) : (int, string) Result =}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad let\%bind a = input () |&gt; atoi in}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad let\%map b = input () |&gt; atoi in}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad a + b} \end{align*} $$
$	exttt{input () |&gt; atoi}$ is syntactic sugar for $	exttt{atoi (input ())}$
Deferred Definition Deferreds allow us to make asynchronous computation. The implementation is a bit more involved, since the idea is computation is queued to a scheduler within a deferred monad. For this reason, the following code is pseudocode.
$$  egin{align*} &amp;	exttt{type &lsquo;a Deferred =}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\quad | Determined of &lsquo;a}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\quad | Undetermined}
ewline &amp;
ewline &amp;	exttt{let return a = Determined a }
ewline &amp;	exttt{let bind a\_def f = &hellip;}
ewline &amp;	exttt{(* f is queued on the scheduler. The return value of the bind}
ewline &amp;	exttt{ * (call it x) resolves immediately to undetermined. Upon f&rsquo;s}
ewline &amp;	exttt{ * execution completion, x becomes a determined. Monadic chains}
ewline &amp;	exttt{ * (bind to bind to &hellip; to bind to map) continue asynchronously}
ewline &amp;	exttt{ * on x.}
ewline &amp;	exttt{ *}
ewline &amp;	exttt{ * These deferred monadic chains are &ldquo;upon&rdquo; computations.}
ewline &amp;	exttt{ *)}
ewline \end{align*} $$
Use Suppose we have a function write a function to crawl a webpage and click all links and print visited urls. The function halts once it has reached a given depth (all links on the first page result have depth $1$; all of their links have depth $2$; etc).
Here are the functions we are given to use:
$	exttt{print: string -&gt; unit}$ outputs to $	exttt{stdout}$ $	exttt{curl: string -&gt; string Deferred}$ queries the web for an html page given its web address $	exttt{get\_links: string -&gt; string List}$ grabs a list of all links on an html page $	exttt{List.map: &lsquo;a List -&gt; (&lsquo;a -&gt; &lsquo;b) -&gt; &lsquo;b List}$ takes a list of items and performs a computation on all of its elements $	exttt{Deferred.all: &lsquo;a Deferred List -&gt; &lsquo;a List Deferred}$ transforms a list of deferreds into a single deferred holding a list Notice the $	exttt{List.map}$. Indeed there exists a list monad! We will not be covering it.
$$  egin{align*} &amp;	exttt{let crawl (i : int) (url : string) : unit Deferred =}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad let () = print url in}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad if i = 0 then return () else}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad let j = i - 1 in}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad let\%bind html = curl url in}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad let links = get\_links html in}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad let crawls = List.map links (crawl j) in}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad let\%map (\_ : unit List) = Deferred.all crawls in}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad ()} \end{align*} $$
Note that $	exttt{crawl}$ is non-blocking. If we call it, it will immediately return a $	exttt{unit Deferred}$ and we can continue the program ($	exttt{crawl}$ is queued by the scheduler). If at any point, we want to block until $	exttt{crawl}$ completes, we can monadic bind on the $	exttt{unit Deferred}$ return value.
$$  egin{align*} &amp;	exttt{let unit\_def = crawl 5 &ldquo;https://www.wikipedia.org&rdquo; in}
ewline &amp;	exttt{(* &hellip; do some stuff &hellip; *)}
ewline &amp;	exttt{let\%map () = unit\_def in ()}
ewline \end{align*} $$

Introduction Suppose a class and its two children have the following structures.
$$  egin{align*} &amp;	exttt{class Pet:}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad string name}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad int age} &amp;
ewline &amp;
ewline &amp;	exttt{class Cat extends Pet:}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad string catBreed}
ewline &amp;	ext{}
ewline &amp;	exttt{class Dog extends Pet:}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad string dogBreed} \end{align*} $$
So maybe a person wants to keep track of their pets. Since both $	exttt{Cat}$ and $	exttt{Dog}$ are subtypes of $	exttt{Pet}$, we can store them in a $	exttt{Pet}$ array.
$$	exttt{Pet[] pets}$$
Note that elements in $	exttt{pets}$ won&rsquo;t know if they are a $	exttt{Cat}$ or $	exttt{Dog}$ so we can only access fields that belong to $	exttt{Pet}$ ($	exttt{name}$ and $	exttt{age}$).
Single Inheritance If a $	exttt{Pet}$ doesn&rsquo;t know if it is a $	exttt{Cat}$ or a $	exttt{Dog}$, we need to make sure that the procedure for accessing $	exttt{name}$ and $	exttt{age}$ is the same in both of its children.
Fields What if we put the parent ($	exttt{Pet}$) fields at the top of the memory structure.
p n e a a t m g e e * c a n t c a a B a m g r t e e e * e d * d o n g d a a B o m g r g e e e * e d * Strings are just pointers (*) since there is no bound on string length.
Now, no matter what a $	exttt{Pet pet}$ actually is, $	exttt{pet+0x0}$ is going to be $	exttt{name}$, and $	exttt{pet+0x8}$ is going to be $	exttt{age}$.
This is in our theoretical memory model, though the effect would be similar in your favorite programming language.
Non-virtual Functions Think of non-virtual functions as just normal class methods. We will discuss virtual functions afterwards.
Now, let&rsquo;s add a function to our class hierarchy.
$$  egin{align*} &amp;	exttt{class Pet:}
