ewline &amp;	exttt{(.data+0x0)(dog)} \end{align*} $$
We save space on every object holding a pointer to $	exttt{noise}$ ($	exttt{+0x8}$ size per object).
Virtual Functions Introduction The heart of inheritance is the concept of a virtual function. The idea is that an inherited method can take different definitions depending on the class hierarchy lineage.
Let&rsquo;s take our code from above and modify it so that $	exttt{noise}$ is a virtual function.
Other class data omitted.
$$  egin{align*} &amp;	exttt{class Pet:}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad void noise():}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad\qquad print(&ldquo;pet noises&rdquo;)}
ewline &amp;	ext{}
ewline &amp;	exttt{class Cat extends Pet:}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad void noise():}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad\qquad print(&ldquo;meow&rdquo;)}
ewline &amp;	ext{}
ewline &amp;	exttt{class Dog extends Pet:}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad void noise():}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad\qquad print(&ldquo;bark&rdquo;)} \end{align*} $$
The children can override the definition of a virtual method (in this case, $	exttt{noise}$).
Note that if the child does not provide a definition override, it keeps the parent&rsquo;s definition (recursively).
$$  egin{align*} &amp;	exttt{class Fish extends Pet:}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad string color}
ewline &amp;	ext{}
ewline &amp;	exttt{Fish fish}
ewline &amp;	exttt{fish.noise()\qquad	hickspace	hickspace// &ldquo;pet noises&rdquo;}
ewline &amp;	ext{}
ewline &amp;	exttt{class Betta extends Fish:}
ewline &amp;	exttt{\qquad string bettaSpecies}
ewline &amp;	ext{}
ewline &amp;	exttt{Betta betta}
ewline &amp;	exttt{betta.noise()\qquad// &ldquo;pet noises&rdquo;} \end{align*} $$
The issue now is that we cannot know at compile-time which virtual function (in this case $	exttt{noise}$) to call.
$$  egin{align*} &amp;	exttt{Pet[] pets = [Cat(), Dog()]}
ewline &amp;	exttt{pets[0].noise()\qquad// Cat.noise() -&gt; &ldquo;meow&rdquo;}
ewline &amp;	exttt{pets[1].noise()\qquad// Dog.noise() -&gt; &ldquo;bark&rdquo;} \end{align*} $$
One (naive) solution is to again provide the function pointer as part of the object&rsquo;s structure.
