The worst-case time complexity is $\mathcal{O}(\log n)$ since at worst $n$ becomes a power of $2$, and we have to flip all of its significant bits.
Amortized Analysis Theorem The amortized time cost is at most $2$. Proof Consider $n$ (for large $n$) executions beginning at any state. $A_0$ flips every execution. $A_1$ flips every other execution. $A_2$ flips every 4 executions. $A_k$ flips every $2^k$ executions. The total cost is the sum of these flips.
$$n +  rac{n}{2} +  rac{n}{4} + &hellip; \leq 2n$$ Thus, the average per execution is at most $2\in\mathcal{O}(1)$. The &ldquo;beginning at any state&rdquo; is important. Otherwise, our analysis is not generalizable.
