The worst-case time complexity is $\mathcal{O}(n)$ since at worst $n$ becomes a power of $2$, and we have to flip all of its significant bits ($1+2+4+&hellip;+ rac{n}{2}+n\leq2n$).
Amortized Analysis Theorem The amortized time cost is at most $\log_2 (n) + 1$. Proof Consider $n$ (for large $n$) executions beginning at any state. $A_0$ flips every execution for a cost of $1$. $A_1$ flips every other execution for a cost of $2$. $A_2$ flips every 4 executions for a cost of $4$. $A_k$ flips every $2^k$ executions for a cost of $2^k$. $n$ has $\lfloor\log_2 n + 1floor$ significant bits.
The total cost is the sum of these flips.
$$\underbrace{n + 2\cdot rac{n}{2} + 4\cdot rac{n}{4} + &hellip;}_{\lfloor\log_2 n + 1floor} = n\lfloor\log_2 n + 1floor$$ Thus, the average per execution is $\lfloor\log_2 n + 1floor\in\mathcal{O}(\log n)$. Unbounded Array Problem We want to store a linear stream of data. We start with an Array $\mathcal{A}$ of memory space of size $1$. Every new append inserts into $\mathcal{A}$. If an append is attempted when $\mathcal{A}$ is completely filled, we must reallocate memory at double the size and re-insert previous data before inserting the new data.
It costs $1$ to insert one slot of data.
